When Horace says that the defeat of Hannibal by the elder Scipio, and the destruction of Carthage by the younger, do not hold up their name more nobly than the Muse of Calabria, —who does not sup- ply, in his own mind, ‘which was employed in doing honour to the elder'?'' To me the meaning seems clear enough. Just as Horace, Lib. 1.‚ Carm. xii. v. 46, makes the name of Marcellus, who took Syra· cuse‚ stand for all his family, and include the young Marcellus, so he here makes the name of Africanus stand for the whole family, and in- clude especially the younger Scipio. Or, as Ritter expresses it, the fame of the elder Scipio, recorded by Ennius, was revived in the destruc- tion of Carthage by the younger.
